# Contract: CurrentUserLight query — additive change

**File**: `src/domain/community/userCurrent/CurrentUserProvider/CurrentUserLight.graphql`
**Operation**: query `CurrentUserLight`
**Change type**: additive (no field removed, no rename)

## Diff

```diff
 query CurrentUserLight {
   me {
     user {
       ...UserDetailsLight
+      settings {
+        id
+        designVersion
+      }
       account {
         id
         authorization {
           id
           myPrivileges
         }
         license {
           id
           availableEntitlements
         }
       }
     }
   }
 }
```

## Result shape (post-codegen, confirmed against deployed schema 2026-05-13)

```ts
// Excerpt of the regenerated CurrentUserLightQuery type
me: {
  user: {
    // ...existing UserDetailsLight fields
    settings: {
      id: string;
      designVersion: number; // server returns Int (non-null): 1 (old), 2 (new), 3+ reserved
    };
    account: {
      // ...unchanged
    } | null;
  } | null;
}
```

## Consumer

`CurrentUserProvider.tsx` exposes `designVersion: 1 | 2 | undefined` on its returned model. Mapping rule:

```ts
const raw = data?.me?.user?.settings?.designVersion;
const designVersion: 1 | 2 | undefined =
  raw === 1 || raw === 2 ? raw : undefined;
```

Values outside `{1, 2}` (e.g. `3+`, or absent because the user is unauthenticated and the query was skipped) collapse to `undefined` and are treated as "no preference" by `useDesignVersionSync` (no reconciliation).

## Cache normalization

The Apollo cache normalizes by `UserSettings.id`. We select `settings { id designVersion }` (rather than just `designVersion`) so the new field merges cleanly into the same cache entry already populated by the heavier `userSettings` query in `userSettingsFragment`. Without the `id`, Apollo would synthesize an object identity for the `settings` object and emit dev warnings when the two queries' results meet in the cache.

